The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Pratibha talks tough on border attack
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Pratibha talks tough on border attack
          MUZAFFAR RAINA                           Pratibha Patil aims with an AK-47 recovered from militants near the Tangdhar sector. (PTI)                                  
	Baramulla, May 23: President Pratibha Patil today said any attack on the borders will be dealt with firmly, the assurance coming days after Pakistani troops repeated ceasefire violations in Jammu and Kashmir.        
	I am confident that we will deal firmly with any attack on our borders, the President, the supreme commander of the armed forces, said while visiting the forward areas in Tangdhar in north Kashmirs Kupwara district.         
	Pratibha is on a four-day visit to the state, her first after being elected to the top post last year.        
	I go back with the satisfaction that the countrys borders are secure in your hands. I pray for your long life and hope you continue to achieve your aim by your hard work and zeal.        
	The President, accompanied by Governor S.K. Sinha, chief minister Ghulam Nabi Azad and army chief General Deepak Kapoor, met soldiers for around 30 minutes at Tangdhars Shararat post, at an altitude of 10,000 feet.        
	She saw the conditions in which soldiers live on the Line of Control and went inside their bunkers. She expressed happiness after finding the soldiers in high spirits. She was also shown the villages on the other side of LoC, in PoK, defence spokesperson Lt Colonel A.K. Mathur said.        
	Addressing the troops later, the President praised them for their bravery, dedication and morale. I know that you are performing duties for the nation thousands of miles away from your homes. The country recognises your untiring services. Our governments efforts have been to provide better facilities to you and your families.        
	The President told the soldiers that constant efforts were being made to modernise the armed forces. It is our continuous effort to modernise the armed forces by providing them state-of-the-art weaponry and good training.        
	She also spoke highly of the armys operations for civilians, saying these were providing succour to the states people. I know that you are working for the betterment of civilians, besides performing duties on borders. The people have been benefited by your contribution.         
	On her arrival earlier in the day, the President was received by Air Commodore Ramesh Goyal, the air officer commanding of the Srinagar air base. She inspected a guard of honour by Indian Air Force personnel.                                                                                                                                                                         
